        </statement>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            For which types of functions will this method for finding slope fail? Why does it fail?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="exer-field-goal">
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Analyze the tile pattern in <xref ref="fig-exer-tile-pattern"/>. Draw the figure for Step 0 and for Step 5.
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="fig-exer-tile-pattern">
          <caption>Tile Pattern for <xref ref="exer-field-goal"/></caption>
          <image source="tile-pattern-field-goal" width="90%">
            <description></description>
          </image>
        </figure>
      </introduction>

      <task xml:id="exer-field-goal-a">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Describe the pattern you used to draw Step 5. How do you know you are correct?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            What equation models the relationship between the step number and the number of tiles needed. How do you know?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            As the pattern grows, what physical features of the design are represented by the slope? How do you know?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            What part of the design is responsible for the <m>y</m>-intercept? How do you know?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task xml:id="exer-field-goal-e">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Suppose the tile pattern did not have the tiles creating the stem at the bottom of each figure above. How would the equation change? Explain your thinking.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Would the graph of the design in <xref ref="exer-field-goal-e"/> have the same <m>y</m>-intercept, smaller <m>y</m>-intercept, or larger <m>y</m>-intercept than the graph of the design in <xref ref="exer-field-goal-a"/>? How do you know?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find an equation to fit this new design. Explain your work.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Complete the student page, <xref text="title" ref="act-analyze-more-tiles"/>. Follow the directions on the student page. Be prepared to share your work with your group and class.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For the non-linear patterns in the student page, <xref text="title" ref="act-analyze-more-tiles"/>, 
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Explain how you know the pattern is not linear. Use more than one representation to justify your choices.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task xml:id="exer-pattern-g">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use a table to show how the number of tiles is growing. Remember not to simplify the table values too soon. Describe how each pattern is growing in words. For example, consider Pattern G. Create a table like the one in <xref ref="tbl-more-tile-patterns"/>. Notice that each quantity shows how it arises from the one before it. How does the number of tiles in step 4 relate to the number of tiles in step 3? How does the step number relate to the number of tiles for that step?  Back up the table from step 2 to step 1 then to step 0. 
          </p>
          <table xml:id="tbl-more-tile-patterns">
            <title>Table for <xref ref="exer-pattern-g"/></title>
            <tabular halign="center" top="minor" left="minor">
              <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                <cell right="minor"><m>x</m></cell>
                <cell right="minor"><m>y</m></cell>
              </row>

              <row bottom="minor">
                <cell right="minor">0</cell>
                <cell right="minor"><nbsp/></cell>
              </row>

              <row bottom="minor">
                <cell right="minor">1</cell>
                <cell right="minor"><nbsp/></cell>
              </row>

              <row bottom="minor">
                <cell right="minor">2</cell>
                <cell right="minor"><m>4 = 2 \cdot 2 = 2^2</m></cell>
              </row>

              <row bottom="minor">
                <cell right="minor">3</cell>
                <cell right="minor"><m>8 = 2 \cdot 2 \cdot 2 = 2^3</m></cell>
              </row>

              <row bottom="minor">
                <cell right="minor">4</cell>
                <cell right="minor"><nbsp/></cell>
              </row>

              <row bottom="minor">
                <cell right="minor">5</cell>
                <cell right="minor"><nbsp/></cell>
              </row>
            </tabular>
          </table>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Stretch your equation-finding abilities to find equations for some of the non-linear tile patterns. Your work with tables can help. Explain how you know your equations are correct.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            You have seen a pattern similar to Pattern H twice before. Do you recall where? How is Pattern H related to the patterns you saw previously? How might you find an equation to model this pattern?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Consider both student pages, <xref text="title" ref="act-analyze-tiles"/> and <xref text="title" ref="act-analyze-more-tiles"/> Choose 3 tile patterns from each page. For each tile pattern:
        </p>
